  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "g7QEwO+hYuhPSs4pWemddF24Ycc=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:45.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Claim\n\nGSOC notifications have two hard constraints: the receiving node must be a **full node** (light nodes do not sync neighborhood chunks) and writers must use **mutable stamps** (to avoid bucket exhaustion on frequent signals).\n\n## Evidence\n\n- Light nodes do not store neighborhood chunks \u2014 they cannot see incoming SOC updates addressed to their neighborhood, so GSOC subscription is a full-node-only feature\n- Each GSOC send is a new SOC = a new chunk consuming a bucket slot. With immutable stamps, frequent notifications hot-spot a bucket and fail the batch well before TTL\n- Mutable stamps replace the oldest chunk in the overflowing bucket, so the notification channel self-garbage-collects\n\n## Why it matters\n\nAny architecture that uses GSOC for collaboration coordination (e.g. \"Connect instances register with a switchboard via GSOC\") has two environmental preconditions that affect deployment: the receiving instance must run a full node, and the stamp provisioning flow must request `immutableFlag: false`. Both are easy to get wrong silently.\n",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:45.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:45.000Z"
    }
  },
